1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is the Supreme Court?

The Supreme Court of India is the highest judicial authority in the country.

📌 Established under Article 124

Functions:

Protect Constitution
Protect Fundamental Rights
Interpret laws
Resolve disputes
🔵 Composition

Supreme Court consists of:

Chief Justice of India (CJI)
Other judges appointed by President

📌 Parliament can increase number of judges.

🔹 Appointment of Judges

Judges are appointed by the President.

Collegium System
CJI + senior judges recommend appointments

📌 Judicial independence is important.

🔴 Qualifications of SC Judge

A person must:

Be citizen of India
Be High Court judge for 5 years
OR
Advocate in High Court for 10 years
OR
Distinguished jurist
🔹 Tenure & Removal
Retirement age: 65 years
Removal:
By impeachment in Parliament
Grounds:
Proven misbehavior
Incapacity

📌 Difficult process to ensure independence.

🔹 Jurisdictions of Supreme Court
1️⃣ Original Jurisdiction

Disputes between:

Centre & states
States
2️⃣ Appellate Jurisdiction

Hears appeals from High Courts.

3️⃣ Advisory Jurisdiction

President can seek advice under Article 143.

4️⃣ Writ Jurisdiction

Under Article 32 for Fundamental Rights.

🔹 Judicial Review

Supreme Court can declare laws unconstitutional.

📌 Basic feature of Constitution.

🔹 Judicial Activism & PIL
PIL = Public Interest Litigation

Allows public to approach courts for social justice.

🔹 Important Concepts
Term	Meaning
Judicial Review	Review constitutionality
PIL	Public interest case
Article 32	Constitutional remedies
Guardian of Constitution	Supreme Court
